COPS nabbed three suspects in connection with the theft of Metrorail copper cables on Wednesday night. Western Cape police spokeswoman Sergeant Noloyiso Rwexana said the arrests in Bishop Lavis, Cape Town, came after ongoing investigations to combat crime on train lines. “Police responded to a tip-off about criminals allegedly operating in the Bonteheuwel area and stealing Prasa cables at night,” she said. if(typeof za24_DisplayAd != "undefined") za24_DisplayAd("300x250","2");<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>Metrorail spokeswoman Riana Scott said: “We are obviously thrilled with the result and encourage communities to continue reporting apparent crimes in progress and suspicious activity near railway precincts.” Sergeant Rwexana said the arrested suspects, aged between 23 and 37, were caught red-handed with Metrorail copper cables.“They will appear in the Bishop Lavis Magistrates Court on charges of theft,” she said.Western Cape police commissioner Lieutenant-General Khombinkosi Jula encouraged cops to continuing working with community members. Commuters were also happy to hear about the arrests. Nthabiseng Molebo (33) from Langa said: “At least there is hope that cops can deal with these thugs who put hundreds of thousands of people at a disadvantage.” She said the recent disruption of service on the central line had cost her money. “I bought two monthly tickets for my kids but ended up having to pay for taxis too,” she said.